You have hit on the exact breaking point of the proxy architecture. Building your own dedicated VS Code extension interface is absolutely the right next step.Relying on the official GitHub Copilot Chat interface as a proxy host introduces a major architectural mismatch. The Copilot extension expects a standard, linear conversational assistant. It is constantly injecting its own background context, hidden system instructions, and UI state tracking. When your stateful, multi-step MonsterTools orchestration engine tries to feed complex agent loops through that restricted pipeline, Copilot’s internal UI code intercepts and breaks the stream, leading to unexplained dropouts, hidden formatting errors, and timeouts.By shifting MonsterTools into its own dedicated VS Code extension, you can explicitly establish the Gateway-to-Workspace paradigm.The Gateway-to-Workspace ArchitectureWhen your extension initializes, it treats the active VS Code workspace as a living database. MonsterTools ceases to be a passive chatbot; it becomes an active runtime manager for that specific directory.



