Why a Dedicated Extension Solves Your Current Bugs1. Complete Control Over Raw Streaming (No Copilot Interference)Your custom interface can bypass standard HTTP endpoints entirely if needed. You can use standard Visual Studio Code Webview Panels paired with high-speed WebSockets or local IPC (Inter-Process Communication). This prevents any external extension from parsing, formatting, or breaking your local JSON/XML agent arguments before they reach your C# backend.2. Visualizing the "Agent Mind" (The Unreal Engine Paradigm)Because your platform background is heavily inspired by Unreal Engine, you know that developers need to see state. Copilot Chat hides everything in a text window. With your own Webview, you can build a UI that shows:The Active Worker: A visual indicator showing when FileSystemWorker is reading code vs. when BuildWorker is compiling.The Agent Thinking Loop: A step-by-step rolling trace log of how the local LLM is diagnosing a build error.A "Rollback" Trigger: A prominent UI button that lets the developer instantly revert the workspace to a stable git state if the local agent makes a faulty logic leap.3. Deep Workspace Context BindingA custom extension can natively tap into the vscode.workspace API. The moment a project loads, MonsterTools can silently run its file workers to index the directory layout into your C# state machine. When the local LLM needs to reason about a bug, the extension doesn't need to read the whole file; it sends a precise map coordinates packet (e.g., File.cs, Line 42-56) directly to the model.How to Build This Extension Pipeline EffortlesslyYou don’t need to be a veteran TypeScript engineer to build a robust VS Code extension frontend. Because you are highly proficient in C#, you can offload almost all structural complexity to your native backend.Keep the TypeScript Extension Slim: Treat your VS Code extension strictly as a "dumb terminal" or thin UI wrapper. Use the standard Yeoman VS Code Extension Generator to scaffold a basic Webview extension.Launch the C# Backend on Startup: Configure the TypeScript extension’s activate method to silently launch your compiled MonsterTools C# execution loop binary in the background as a child process.Bridge via Local WebSockets: Let the VS Code Webview panel communicate with the local running C# engine via standard JSON-RPC over a local loopback port (e.g., localhost:xxxxx). Your C# engine remains the master coordinator, updating the UI dynamically whenever a local worker executes an action.This migration cleanly decouples you from the commercial cloud ecosystems. MonsterTools becomes a completely independent, hyper-focused, local IDE platform.